In message &lt;1184593255.340 ... @storm.cam.harlequin.co.uk&gt;, Mike Edie
&lt;mike.e ... @nospamthankyoumam.com&gt; writes

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;I'm always curious to know how much gigging a band has to do in order
&gt;to make say £25k each a year and make it a full time job.
">

£25k a year to share between the bandmembers is more realistic.
:-)
Banding is the worst paid job on the folk scene. Even if you get paid
decent rates for gigs the expenses are high and there are a lot of
bandmates to share with.

We just about made a living as a trio with Artisan, but if £25k per year
is your idea of a basic income I'd like to come and live on your street.

You might make that as a soloist _if_ you're very lucky, much in demand,
have a good agent, run your own record company and sell an average of 10
CDs a gig.

Don't forget the expenses include not just travelling to and from the
gig,  but poster and flyer printing, advertising, office expenses, i.e.
running a computer with broadband and maintaining your web site, your
agent's 15% or the cost of getting your own gigs, cost of maintaining a
mailing list - including some paper mail outs (our last paper mail shot
cost £800). Then there's your gig clothes, hairdressing and the stupid
stuff we do to look halfway decent - which might even include the more
expensive of two options for dentistry or contact lenses for stagewear
or nail-wraps for guitarists.
That's before you start on the instruments, PA, vehicle, running costs
and maintenance. Oh yes, and union fees.

Did I forget anything, Dick?

So presume you are a soloist and you are lucky enough to get 150 gigs a
year at an average of £150 a gig - that's still only £22,500. Let's say
you average 5 CD sales per gig with a profit of £7 per CD after
recording and manufacturing and royalty costs - that's another £5,250.

So your basic wage is up to £27,750 before you start to deduct all the
above expenses.

You'll be living on about £13,000 - £14,000 a year if you're lucky.

Even if you are well in demand and you average £200 per gig, that's
still only another £7,5k  and some expenses - like agent's percentages -
rise proportionately so you'll be lucky if you see £5k out of that, so
then you're up to, maybe, £19k a year - but guess what... the tax man
and NI dept. is going to take about 3k of that, so your income is about
£16k per year. Of course, some well established soloists command fees
well in excess of £200 per gig, but many on even the middle rungs of the
ladder are still gigging in folk clubs for £80 or £100 per night when
they have to.

And remember, generally, the higher the fee, the fewer gigs per year.

Say you're part of a band that asks for 5k as a festival fee... how many
gigs a year does that band expect to do? (How many festivals have that
kind of budget?) How many members in the band? Do they pay extra for a
sound man and maybe a manager?

If you are going to become a full time folk musician I can tell you now
that you'll be doing it because you can't bear to do anything else, not
because you think it's a good way to make a decent living. Far more
musicians fail to earn a full time wage than succeed. I know a lot of
full time musicians who couldn't do what they do if they didn't have a
spouse with a 'real' job.

When we kicked the day jobs in the head and went full time with Artisan
in 1989 we would never have been able to manage if not for the fact that
we'd bought our house at the right time (in 1971) and paid off the
mortgage, so our overheads were minimal. We didn't used to pay ourselves
gig by gig; we put it into a pot and paid ourselves a monthly wage -
whether or not there were any gigs that month. Our first monthly wage
was £350 each.

Even in 1989 that wasn't a lot.

I wish I could say they went up rapidly from there.
:-)

People who knew we'd packed in the day jobs used to come and ask if we
could earn 'enough' as musicians and our answer was always, 'Define
enough.' Despite the fact that we've never had (still don't have) money
for luxuries, I wouldn't go back on that decision in 1989.

To go back to your first question, to earn £25k a year as a (5 piece)
band-member the band would have to be doing 200 gigs a year at £1,000
per gig and selling CDs like mad to give you a clear take home pay of
£125 per gig after expenses.

Or 100 gigs a year at £2,000 per gig

What are the chances of that?

:-)

Don't give up the day job... at least, not for the money.

Jacey

