Ah. The dotcom boom was almost founded on the idea of
pay-per-listen/view, with the expected idyll of a global jukebox - all
copyrighted material held centrally, no need to buy anything, you get
charged a &quot;micropayment&quot; for use of it. Enough fibre was plumbed in back
then to allow the infrastructure to cope with the expected migration of
all such media (including telly) to cable.

Except it didn't happen - not because of the technology, which was there
(pretty much [1]), but because of established business models.
Basically, the music/movie sales/licensing cartels (let's be honest)
liked things just the way they were. It worked for them just fine.
Hollywood etc just was not, and is not, ready to consider alternative
models. And they won't until they have no option. This is, maybe,
starting to happen with music (not yet with movies).

Also the banks etc weren't ready to cope with micropayments. And
(arguably) still aren't. Same problem: they like it the way it is. (5
working days to clear an electronic payment? Bah.)

[1] After the dotcom bust, it was estimated that 90% of all cable
installed was dark (unused). I was working at the time for a telecomms
company... which folded shortly thereafter...

