I want to put the new Outside Track album up for digital download via
CDBaby (and thence to iTunes etc.) but MCPS tells me they can't handle
the royalties on digital sales and I'm supposed to seek permission from
all the individual (international) copyright holders/publishers (and
there are many because of multiple writers of tunes included in tune
sets). If I don't seek permission (or if they don't respond - which some
of them haven't) I can still do it legally, but I'm supposed to account
on a monthly basis and it seems daft getting a US bank draft each month
for the nine downloads of a Dar Williams song at 8 cents per download.

The popular take on it seems to be 'publish and be damned' - set aside
the royalties and account to the copyright owners once a year or twice a
year if the money builds up to a significant amount.

Dammit I _want_ to stay legal on this. We've paid the MCPS licence for
the pressing and sales are really encouraging so far, but we don't want
to miss out on digital sales. I'd be happy to pay a digital licence in
advance of sales just to show good faith. You'd think they could do it
as a percentage of your MCPS bill. OK it might not be entirely
representative of the exact sales figures, but it would be a token
gesture to keep us legal.

www.bedspringmusic.co.uk

